    },
    {
      "id": "F-bsNYeFE8PaV-Bn2C9YX",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 139.12212476591446,
      "y": -1844.5789777533344,
      "width": 1726.9666748046875,
      "height": 3300,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2S",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 89596847,
      "version": 11030,
      "versionNonce": 792622145,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1766735430738,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\nDropbox\n\nFunctional Requirement - \n    1. Users can upload files to remote storage\n    2. Users can download files from remote storage\n    3. Users can automatically sync files across devices\n\nNon-Functional Requirement - \n    1. The system should prioritize availability. Eventual consistency is fine across devices\n    2. With 100M Daily Active Users, the system should be able to sustain 1K requests/sec.\n    3. The System should be able to upload 50GB file\n    4. The system should be able to resume upload and download, given the max is 50GB.\n    5. The system should be able to download the files in real time (< 200 ms)\n    6. The system should be able to handle the sync latency within 1 minute. If a user requests\n       within 1 minute, prioritize availability and show them old content.\n\nAPI Contracts - \n    \n1. POST upload/ --> S3 Link and status code 200\n\n{\n      UserId:\n      FileId:\n      TotalChunks:\n      FileSize\n      ....FileMetadata:  \n      Timestamp:\n      DeviceUploadIP:\n}\n\n\n2. GET download/<FileId>\n {\n      FileId:\n      UserId:\n      S3Link:\n      Timestamp:\n }\n\n\n3. POST sync/<UserId> --> Push notification to the devices to refresh and trigger the download of Changed File Ids.\n{\n      FilesToBeSynced: <FileId, TimestampChanged>\n}\n\n\n\nHigh Level Design \n\n\n1. Users can upload files to remote storage\n      a. The Device1 makes a request to upload a file to the Dropbox. The Dropbox generates S3 presigned URL link and update the database\n      b. The Dropbox returns the S3 presigned URL to the Device1.\n      c. The Device1 makes a request directly to S3 to upload the file.\n      d. Once the upload to S3 is done, the Device makes a PATCH request to Dropbox service which marks the status as COMPLETED.\n\n2. Users can download files to remote storage\n      a. Device2 makes a request to retrieve all files for that user. It queries the FILE Table based on userId and COMPLETED status and return the list of S3Link.\n      b. Device2 directly makes a request to S3 to download the files using HTTP request and persist in its local DB.\n\nWhen will Device detect edits in its own local Device folder ?\n      a. If Device1 keeps on editing his picture and keep on persisting in Dropbox app with netoff, then the device will have LastLocalModifiedTimestamp with status\n          as PENDING_UPLOAD\n     b. Once the LastServerModifiedTimestamp is different from LastLocalModifedTimestamp, it is basically an indication that the device needs synchronization or upload\n         the latest edit.\n     c. FileWatcher could be a great tool to update LastLocalModifiedTimestamp\n \n\n3. Users can automatically sync files across devices\n        a. We can have a Sync Service which listens to the Database and only react when a File is uploaded with status COMPLETED.\n        b. Once the Sync Service is notified via the POST API, it queries the list of devices from the USER table and sends a push device notification to the Device2\n            containing S3 presigned URL, FileId, LastModifiedTimestamp.\n        c. When Device2 receives a notification, it checks that the LastModifiedTimestamp > LastServerModifiedTimestamp, that means it is a new copy.\n        d. At the same time, Device2 may have some local edits. If it persists the new change, local edits of Device2 are gone. \n        e. Considering there are no local edits which means LastLocalModifiedTimestamp == LastServerModifiedTimestamp and LastModifiedTimestamp > LastServerModifiedTimestamp\n            then Device2 can simply persist that information in its local DB and call S3 to download the image\n        f. If Device2 needs to safely protect its local edits, it needs to follows the protocol of first upload and then download.\n        g. So, Device2 will reject the notification of new server copy and it will proceed to make a request to Dropbox Service.\n        h. The dropbox service will see that Timestamp for the POST request < LastModifiedTimestamp -That means Device2 had made local edits on an old copy and hence needs to be updated.\n        i. Hence Dropbox will reject the request with a message saying refresh the content.\n\n4. Users make edits to the same file at the same time\n        a. If Device1 and Device 2 made edits to the same file, we need a conflict resolution service.\n        b. Both of these devices will have to follow the principle of Upload and then Download.\n        c. Both of them will make a request to the Dropbox to update the File. Both the devices can be connected to different instances of the Dropbox Service\n        d. Hence, we need a conflict Resolution Service which will make the decision of which request to process. If the userId is same for multiple requests,\n            The Conflict Resolution Service will discard all the other requests and generate a presigned S3 URL and return to the Device which requested the\n             upload Link. Post which, the Dropbox Instance will update the S3URL (pre-signed) and status as IN_PROGRESS.\n        e. Sync Service which listens to the Database and only react when a File is uploaded with status COMPLETED.\n        f. Once the Sync Service is notified via the POST API, it queries the list of devices from the USER table and sends a push device notification to the Device2\n            containing S3 presigned URL, FileId, LastModifiedTimestamp.\n\n\n5. The system should be able to resume upload and download, given the max is 50GB.\n      a. If Device1 needs to upload a file of size 50GB, the device1 needs to strip the file into smaller sizes preferably for multi-part upload.\n      b. Given the max is 50GB, we can think of stripping the file of chunks 10MB and update the local database with FileChunkMetadata.\n      c. Now Device1 makes a request to upload 50GB and the Dropbox service uploads the information to the FILE table. \n      d. Device1 adds a new param to the POST request with TotalChunks. The DropboxService generates pre-signed URL of the same number\n          and returns it to the Device1\n      e. Device1 updates its FileChunkMetadata database. Now, Device1 keeps on uploading the file chunk with S3. As every file chunk is uploaded, it updates its \n          local database.\n      f. Even the network connection is dropped, the device can resume from the chunks which didn't upload.\n      g. Once all the chunks are uploaded, it makes a PATCH request to the Dropbox Service to mark the upload as successful. To seriously validate the client's behavior,\n           the dropbox makes a request to mark the end of multi-part upload and update the FILE table with S3 presigned URL and Status as Completed.\n      h. When the multi-part upload is completed, S3 itself consolidates all the chunks into a single bucket and provides the S3 URL for the same object.\n      i. So, once the status is COMPLETED, the Sync Service will send a push notification of all the devices to update its FILE database in the local.\n\nWhat happens if Device1 local DB is crashed during upload ? We lose all progress\n     a. So, when Device 1 sends a request to upload the file, the Dropbox starts a  multi-part upload and persists the uploadId in the FILE table\n     b. Post that Device1 shares all its chunk metadata information to the DropBox Service and it creates a table similar to Local DB.\n     c. The Server returns pre-signed URL for all the chunks. Once Device1 uploads the chunk, it updates its local DB and the serverDB.\n     d. Once all the chunks are uploaded, it sends a confirmation request to Dropbox service which validates with S3 that multi-part upload is over,\n         update the S3 URL of the object, LastModifiedTimestamp and deletes the FileChunkMetadata TABLE.\n     e. If Device1 crashes and revives, it can query the DropBox service to provide the list of files whose STATUS is INPROGRESS and then retrieve \n         the file chunk metadata from the server to local.\n     f. Device1 uses the same Client SDK to strip the file and hash them to find the chunk_id which is unique finger print of the chunks and proceeds to \n        upload the chunk whose status is NOT_StARTED\n\n\n6. How to make sync process faster than downloading full files each time they change ?\n      a. Device1 has a local FileChunkMetadata copy and the server also has a FileChunkMetadata copy.\n      b. Any local edits to the file means a change in hash value.\n      c. So, if the LastLocalModifiedTimestamp > LastServerModifiedTimestamp, The Device1 will proceed to strip the file using AWS Client SDK\n         Since the file content changed, AWS Client SDK will strip and prepare a unique fingerprint for every chunk. \n     d. Check there is a change in chunk_id, make a upload request with the specific Chunk. The dropbox will update its FileChunkMetadata after Conflict Resolution,.\n     e. Now, the Dropbox service will have to offload the work to server less Lambda whose purpose will be to start a new multi-upload and will proceed\n         to create complete Upload and then update the FILE table.\n     f. Once the FILE table is updated with status COMPLETED, Sync Service can only contain the modified part (new added and new deleted) that changed and pass it as a new notification.\n     g. The Device2 can just update its own FILE table and FILE CHUNK METADATA table to reflect the new addition and deletion.\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\nDropbox\n\nFunctional Requirement - \n    1. Users can upload files to remote storage\n    2. Users can download files from remote storage\n    3. Users can automatically sync files across devices\n\nNon-Functional Requirement - \n    1. The system should prioritize availability. Eventual consistency is fine across devices\n    2. With 100M Daily Active Users, the system should be able to sustain 1K requests/sec.\n    3. The System should be able to upload 50GB file\n    4. The system should be able to resume upload and download, given the max is 50GB.\n    5. The system should be able to download the files in real time (< 200 ms)\n    6. The system should be able to handle the sync latency within 1 minute. If a user requests\n       within 1 minute, prioritize availability and show them old content.\n\nAPI Contracts - \n    \n1. POST upload/ --> S3 Link and status code 200\n\n{\n      UserId:\n      FileId:\n      TotalChunks:\n      FileSize\n      ....FileMetadata:  \n      Timestamp:\n      DeviceUploadIP:\n}\n\n\n2. GET download/<FileId>\n {\n      FileId:\n      UserId:\n      S3Link:\n      Timestamp:\n }\n\n\n3. POST sync/<UserId> --> Push notification to the devices to refresh and trigger the download of Changed File Ids.\n{\n      FilesToBeSynced: <FileId, TimestampChanged>\n}\n\n\n\nHigh Level Design \n\n\n1. Users can upload files to remote storage\n      a. The Device1 makes a request to upload a file to the Dropbox. The Dropbox generates S3 presigned URL link and update the database\n      b. The Dropbox returns the S3 presigned URL to the Device1.\n      c. The Device1 makes a request directly to S3 to upload the file.\n      d. Once the upload to S3 is done, the Device makes a PATCH request to Dropbox service which marks the status as COMPLETED.\n\n2. Users can download files to remote storage\n      a. Device2 makes a request to retrieve all files for that user. It queries the FILE Table based on userId and COMPLETED status and return the list of S3Link.\n      b. Device2 directly makes a request to S3 to download the files using HTTP request and persist in its local DB.\n\nWhen will Device detect edits in its own local Device folder ?\n      a. If Device1 keeps on editing his picture and keep on persisting in Dropbox app with netoff, then the device will have LastLocalModifiedTimestamp with status\n          as PENDING_UPLOAD\n     b. Once the LastServerModifiedTimestamp is different from LastLocalModifedTimestamp, it is basically an indication that the device needs synchronization or upload\n         the latest edit.\n     c. FileWatcher could be a great tool to update LastLocalModifiedTimestamp\n \n\n3. Users can automatically sync files across devices\n        a. We can have a Sync Service which listens to the Database and only react when a File is uploaded with status COMPLETED.\n        b. Once the Sync Service is notified via the POST API, it queries the list of devices from the USER table and sends a push device notification to the Device2\n            containing S3 presigned URL, FileId, LastModifiedTimestamp.\n        c. When Device2 receives a notification, it checks that the LastModifiedTimestamp > LastServerModifiedTimestamp, that means it is a new copy.\n        d. At the same time, Device2 may have some local edits. If it persists the new change, local edits of Device2 are gone. \n        e. Considering there are no local edits which means LastLocalModifiedTimestamp == LastServerModifiedTimestamp and LastModifiedTimestamp > LastServerModifiedTimestamp\n            then Device2 can simply persist that information in its local DB and call S3 to download the image\n        f. If Device2 needs to safely protect its local edits, it needs to follows the protocol of first upload and then download.\n        g. So, Device2 will reject the notification of new server copy and it will proceed to make a request to Dropbox Service.\n        h. The dropbox service will see that Timestamp for the POST request < LastModifiedTimestamp -That means Device2 had made local edits on an old copy and hence needs to be updated.\n        i. Hence Dropbox will reject the request with a message saying refresh the content.\n\n4. Users make edits to the same file at the same time\n        a. If Device1 and Device 2 made edits to the same file, we need a conflict resolution service.\n        b. Both of these devices will have to follow the principle of Upload and then Download.\n        c. Both of them will make a request to the Dropbox to update the File. Both the devices can be connected to different instances of the Dropbox Service\n        d. Hence, we need a conflict Resolution Service which will make the decision of which request to process. If the userId is same for multiple requests,\n            The Conflict Resolution Service will discard all the other requests and generate a presigned S3 URL and return to the Device which requested the\n             upload Link. Post which, the Dropbox Instance will update the S3URL (pre-signed) and status as IN_PROGRESS.\n        e. Sync Service which listens to the Database and only react when a File is uploaded with status COMPLETED.\n        f. Once the Sync Service is notified via the POST API, it queries the list of devices from the USER table and sends a push device notification to the Device2\n            containing S3 presigned URL, FileId, LastModifiedTimestamp.\n\n\n5. The system should be able to resume upload and download, given the max is 50GB.\n      a. If Device1 needs to upload a file of size 50GB, the device1 needs to strip the file into smaller sizes preferably for multi-part upload.\n      b. Given the max is 50GB, we can think of stripping the file of chunks 10MB and update the local database with FileChunkMetadata.\n      c. Now Device1 makes a request to upload 50GB and the Dropbox service uploads the information to the FILE table. \n      d. Device1 adds a new param to the POST request with TotalChunks. The DropboxService generates pre-signed URL of the same number\n          and returns it to the Device1\n      e. Device1 updates its FileChunkMetadata database. Now, Device1 keeps on uploading the file chunk with S3. As every file chunk is uploaded, it updates its \n          local database.\n      f. Even the network connection is dropped, the device can resume from the chunks which didn't upload.\n      g. Once all the chunks are uploaded, it makes a PATCH request to the Dropbox Service to mark the upload as successful. To seriously validate the client's behavior,\n           the dropbox makes a request to mark the end of multi-part upload and update the FILE table with S3 presigned URL and Status as Completed.\n      h. When the multi-part upload is completed, S3 itself consolidates all the chunks into a single bucket and provides the S3 URL for the same object.\n      i. So, once the status is COMPLETED, the Sync Service will send a push notification of all the devices to update its FILE database in the local.\n\nWhat happens if Device1 local DB is crashed during upload ? We lose all progress\n     a. So, when Device 1 sends a request to upload the file, the Dropbox starts a  multi-part upload and persists the uploadId in the FILE table\n     b. Post that Device1 shares all its chunk metadata information to the DropBox Service and it creates a table similar to Local DB.\n     c. The Server returns pre-signed URL for all the chunks. Once Device1 uploads the chunk, it updates its local DB and the serverDB.\n     d. Once all the chunks are uploaded, it sends a confirmation request to Dropbox service which validates with S3 that multi-part upload is over,\n         update the S3 URL of the object, LastModifiedTimestamp and deletes the FileChunkMetadata TABLE.\n     e. If Device1 crashes and revives, it can query the DropBox service to provide the list of files whose STATUS is INPROGRESS and then retrieve \n         the file chunk metadata from the server to local.\n     f. Device1 uses the same Client SDK to strip the file and hash them to find the chunk_id which is unique finger print of the chunks and proceeds to \n        upload the chunk whose status is NOT_StARTED\n\n\n6. How to make sync process faster than downloading full files each time they change ?\n      a. Device1 has a local FileChunkMetadata copy and the server also has a FileChunkMetadata copy.\n      b. Any local edits to the file means a change in hash value.\n      c. So, if the LastLocalModifiedTimestamp > LastServerModifiedTimestamp, The Device1 will proceed to strip the file using AWS Client SDK\n         Since the file content changed, AWS Client SDK will strip and prepare a unique fingerprint for every chunk. \n     d. Check there is a change in chunk_id, make a upload request with the specific Chunk. The dropbox will update its FileChunkMetadata after Conflict Resolution,.\n     e. Now, the Dropbox service will have to offload the work to server less Lambda whose purpose will be to start a new multi-upload and will proceed\n         to create complete Upload and then update the FILE table.\n     f. Once the FILE table is updated with status COMPLETED, Sync Service can only contain the modified part (new added and new deleted) that changed and pass it as a new notification.\n     g. The Device2 can just update its own FILE table and FILE CHUNK METADATA table to reflect the new addition and deletion.\n\n",
